In my garden, the rainbows are not just painted in the sky. They are real, and they taste like sweet jam.

My favourite is the one that appears after a summer shower. It stretches from the old oak tree to the blue plastic pond. The colours are bright and bold. The red is like a ripe strawberry, and the yellow is as sunny as a dog's fur.

Sometimes, I see a tiny rainbow on the kitchen window. It happens when the sun hits the steam from my tea. It looks like a small, smiling cat. I like to watch it dance across the tiles while I stir my honey.

But the best rainbow is the one that hides in the puddles. When I jump in with my wellies, the water sparkles with every colour of the spectrum. It feels like jumping into a pot of rainbow jelly.

I love these rainbows because they make the world feel magical. They remind me that even after the rain, something beautiful is waiting to be found. [end of text]


